{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5196\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:575:\"<p>The Austin WordPress Meetup has asked me to speak on a topic I use often, wp_localize_script. For those of you who are unfamiliar this allows you to use server-side variables in your client-side JavaScript. I use it for in some of my plugins for taking plugin options and injecting them into the scripts allowing the [&#8230;]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/localizing-wordpress-slides-wordpress-austin-advanced-meetup/\">Localizing WordPress &#8211; Slides From the WordPress Austin Advanced Meetup</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Chris Wiegman\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1324:\"<p>The <a title=\"Austin WordPress Meetup\" href=\"http://wpaustin.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Austin WordPress Meetup</a> has asked me to speak on a topic I use often, <a title=\"wp_lcaolize_script in the WordPress codex\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Function_Reference/wp_localize_script\" target=\"_blank\">wp_localize_script</a>. For those of you who are unfamiliar this allows you to use server-side variables in your client-side JavaScript. I use it for in some of my plugins for taking plugin options and injecting them into the scripts allowing the user much more control over what is happening.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s my slides from the meetup. <span id=\"more-5196\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><object type=\'application/x-shockwave-flash\' wmode=\'opaque\' data=\'http://static.slideshare.net/swf/ssplayer2.swf?id=25862564&doc=localizingwordpress-130903171357-\' width=\'425\' height=\'348\'><param name=\'movie\' value=\'http://static.slideshare.net/swf/ssplayer2.swf?id=25862564&doc=localizingwordpress-130903171357-\' /><param name=\'allowFullScreen\' value=\'true\' /></object></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/localizing-wordpress-slides-wordpress-austin-advanced-meetup/\">Localizing WordPress &#8211; Slides From the WordPress Austin Advanced Meetup</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:83:\"http://bit51.com/localizing-wordpress-slides-wordpress-austin-advanced-meetup/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"Better WP Security 3.5.6\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-6/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-6/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Sat, 24 Aug 2013 15:47:07 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Updates\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5186\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:370:\"<p>The Better WP Security WordPress plugin has received a minor update  to version 3.5.6 which includes a couple of minor bugfixes and a few language enhancements. View the Changelog Download Better WP Security</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-6/\">Better WP Security 3.5.6</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Chris Wiegman\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1026:\"<p><a href=\"http://cdn10.bit51.com/content/uploads/better-wp-security-logo.png\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-3985\" alt=\"Better WP Security\" src=\"http://cdn10.bit51.com/content/uploads/better-wp-security-logo.png\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>The <a title=\"Better WP Security\" href=\"http://bit51.com/software/better-wp-security/\" target=\"_blank\">Better WP Security</a> WordPress plugin has received a minor update  to version 3.5.6 which includes a couple of minor bugfixes and a few language enhancements.</p>\n<p><a title=\"Better Google Tasks Changelog on WordPress.org\" href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/better-wp-security/changelog/\" target=\"_blank\">View the Changelog</a></p>\n<p><strong><a title=\"Better WP Security on WordPress.org\" href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/better-wp-security/\" target=\"_blank\">Download Better WP Security</a></strong></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-6/\">Better WP Security 3.5.6</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:47:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-6/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"10\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:46:\"Better WP Security Crosses 1,000,000 Downloads\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-crosses-1000000/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-crosses-1000000/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 22 Aug 2013 17:22:02 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Bit51 News\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5188\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:512:\"<p>I’m honored to report that this morning the Better WP Security WordPress plugin crossed 1,000,000 downloads. Yes, I’ve known it would hit this milestone for a little while now but I still can’t really believe it. It wasn’t that long ago when I thought it would be great if it had one other download and [&#8230;]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-crosses-1000000/\">Better WP Security Crosses 1,000,000 Downloads</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Chris Wiegman\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1982:\"<p><a href=\"http://cdn10.bit51.com/content/uploads/better-wp-security-logo.png\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-3985\" alt=\"Better WP Security\" src=\"http://cdn10.bit51.com/content/uploads/better-wp-security-logo.png\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" /></a>I’m honored to report that this morning the <a title=\"Better WP Security\" href=\"http://bit51.com/software/better-wp-security/\">Better WP Security</a> WordPress plugin crossed 1,000,000 downloads.</p>\n<p>Yes, I’ve known it would hit this milestone for a little while now but I still can’t really believe it. It wasn’t that long ago when I thought it would be great if it had one other download and not even three years later it has grown to one of the biggest plugins in the <a title=\"Plugins on WordPress.org\" href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress.org plugin repository</a>.</p>\n<p>Thank you to everyone who has downloaded and contributed to this plugin. To the translators, bug testers, bloggers and everyone else who helped bring this plugin to the front of the WordPress security space.<span id=\"more-5188\"></span></p>\n<p>As the first million downloads have now come and gone it is time to start looking forward to the next million and beyond.</p>\n<p>I am still working hard on Better WP Security 4.0 and although it won’t be released as early as I would like it will be out before the end of the year. With it will come improvements to the speed and reliability of all the features already there along with a completely new framework that will allow me to offer premium features as well more free features to all of its users.</p>\n<p>It’s been an awesome ride so far and as Better WP Security’s 3rd year in the repository comes to a close all I can say is…</p>\n<p>…It has only just begun.</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-crosses-1000000/\">Better WP Security Crosses 1,000,000 Downloads</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-crosses-1000000/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"9\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"What Chili’s Is Doing Right\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:44:\"http://bit51.com/what-chilis-is-doing-right/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"http://bit51.com/what-chilis-is-doing-right/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 20 Aug 2013 01:10:26 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Social Media\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5180\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:494:\"<p>There is a little restaurant chain called Chili&#8217;s. maybe you have heard about it. They have some really great fajitas and killer margaritas. Also when I check in on FourSquare I get free chips and salsa. I never forget to check in. Their chips are amazing. Chili&#8217;s has it right when it comes to online [&#8230;]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/what-chilis-is-doing-right/\">What Chili&#8217;s Is Doing Right</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"Michele Butcher\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3898:\"<p><a href=\"http://cdn6.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/08/chillis-logo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-5191\" alt=\"Chili\'s Logo\" src=\"http://cdn7.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/08/chillis-logo-225x192.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"192\" /></a>There is a little restaurant chain called Chili&#8217;s. maybe you have heard about it. They have some really great fajitas and killer margaritas. Also when I check in on <a href=\"http://foursquare.com\" target=\"_blank\">FourSquare</a> I get free chips and salsa. I never forget to check in. Their chips are amazing.</p>\n<div></div>\n<div>Chili&#8217;s has it right when it comes to online and social media advertising. I have yet to encounter a business that surpasses Chili&#8217;s social media marketing strategy.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>What is their secret?</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>They are using all platforms to bring on customers.<span id=\"more-5180\"></span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>Twitter: </strong>If you follow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Chilis\" target=\"_blank\">@Chilis</a> on Twitter they are always engaging with their customers. They respond to their followers very quickly. They retweet their customers tweets about their restaurant visits.  Occasionally they will do Twitter exclusive coupons as well. Recently they had a promotion for a free flat bread pizza.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Foursquare</strong>: The <a href=\"https://foursquare.com/\" target=\"_blank\">FourSquare</a> marketing is what I love the best. I am always forgetting to print out the coupons or I leave the. On the printer. Every single time you check in you are able to get free chips and salsa. Plus for every third time you check in you get your choice of a free desert. For restaurants,  it rarely gets better than this, but it does. Sometimes you can use the coupons with the FourSquare promotions! It amazes me that they make money sometimes.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>Email:</strong>Once to twice a week if you sign up to their email club you get a coupon and sometimes just an advertisement for an upcoming special. They are always just enough so you do not forget about the restaurant but not enough to get annoyed and unsubscribe. Typically the coupons are for something free like a kids meal or appetizer.  You can sign up for them while you dine or on their <a href=\"http://chilis.fbmta.com/forms/chilis/join.aspx?imm_cid=93-9C&amp;inputsource=HP&amp;utm_source=chilis.com&amp;utm_medium=preview_page&amp;utm_campaign=MLHH\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>Facebook:</strong> Chili&#8217;s does their <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/Chilis\" target=\"_blank\">Facebook </a>like most businesses do. They post pictures of their food items, engage with their customers, promote specialty items, and give a place for customers to brag or question anything about the company.  They also have <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/Chilis/app_443870895626234\" target=\"_blank\">smokin&#8217; deals</a> where they offer a coupon for their restaurant.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>Another added bonus that I learned about their restaurant is how they do their fundraising.  The organization doing the fundraiser gets a .PDF file of a coupon to take in their local Chili&#8217;s and as long as there is $500 in sales, the organization makes 10% of the sales from the coupons. That makes fundraising super simple.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>It does not matter what time of day it is, Chili&#8217;s parking lot is always full and most people have rarely had a bad experience during their dining.  I do believe that if they continue with their current marketing strategy and have great customer service they will be in business for a long time.</div>\n</div>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/what-chilis-is-doing-right/\">What Chili&#8217;s Is Doing Right</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:49:\"http://bit51.com/what-chilis-is-doing-right/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"Better Google Tasks 5.0.3\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"http://bit51.com/better-google-tasks-5-0-3/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"http://bit51.com/better-google-tasks-5-0-3/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 19 Aug 2013 00:26:55 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"Updates\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5182\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:454:\"<p>I switched focus for a few days last week to breathe new life into an old project. Better Google Tasks is a Google Chrome extension that allows you full access to all your tasks right from the taskbar and even helps you keep track of what you have on your plate by displaying a task [&#8230;]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/better-google-tasks-5-0-3/\">Better Google Tasks 5.0.3</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Chris Wiegman\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2637:\"<p><a href=\"http://cdn8.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/08/screenshot2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-5183\" alt=\"Better Google Tasks\" src=\"http://cdn5.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/08/screenshot2-225x140.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"140\" /></a>I switched focus for a few days last week to breathe new life into an old project. <a title=\"Better Google Tasks\" href=\"http://bit51.com/software/better-google-tasks/\" target=\"_blank\">Better Google Tasks</a> is a Google Chrome extension that allows you full access to all your tasks right from the taskbar and even helps you keep track of what you have on your plate by displaying a task count and popping up a notification when you have overdue tasks for tasks due today.</p>\n<p>As I mentioned above this isn&#8217;t a new extension. I actually wrote it when I first started using Chrome about 4 years ago but abandoned it in 2011 when I moved from Google Tasks to other task managers. Over the last few months I&#8217;ve found myself bouncing around nearly every task manager on the market (and wasting a lot of time and money in the process). Finally someone right from the top at Google reminded me of this project about a month ago and I realized that it might just be worth picking back up.</p>\n<p>A lot has changed since 2011. The extension had been completely removed from the Chrome store at some point and wouldn&#8217;t work at all with newer versions of Chrome so a complete re-write was in order. It is now faster, smaller and, hopefully, better in just about every way. Unfortunately if you&#8217;re still using the old version though you&#8217;ll need to re-download it. The account I had been using on the Chrome store is no more and I had to start it fresh as a result.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re looking for a simple way to keep track of your task lists give it a shot. If you&#8217;re like me it might just be simple enough to actually use. Of course, don&#8217;t just take my word for it. <a title=\"Google Tasks Extension Brings Super-Fast Task Management to Chrome\" href=\"http://lifehacker.com/5800920/google-tasks-extension-brings-super+fast-task-management-to-chrome\" target=\"_blank\">Here&#8217;s what Lifehacker had to say about it back before I stopped working on it</a>.</p>\n<p><a title=\"Better Google Tasks in the Chrome Store\" href=\"https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/better-google-tasks/ankobamonmpfinilpcolpdealdijoomk\" target=\"_blank\"><strong>Download Better Google Tasks</strong></a></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/better-google-tasks-5-0-3/\">Better Google Tasks 5.0.3</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"http://bit51.com/better-google-tasks-5-0-3/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:45:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:59:\"Virtual Machines… The Holy Grail of Local Web Development\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:74:\"http://bit51.com/virtual-machines-the-holy-grail-of-local-web-development/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"http://bit51.com/virtual-machines-the-holy-grail-of-local-web-development/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 02 Aug 2013 22:16:09 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"Development\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Tools\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5170\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:530:\"<p>I’ve been developing websites for quite a long time, since the 90s to be exact, and over that time the way I work on a project has changed pretty dramatically. Like so many other developers I started out working on plain HTML sites on my local computer and then using FTP to send them to [&#8230;]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/virtual-machines-the-holy-grail-of-local-web-development/\">Virtual Machines&#8230; The Holy Grail of Local Web Development</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Chris Wiegman\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8570:\"<p><a href=\"http://cdn6.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/08/The-Holy-Grail-Of-Web-Development.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-5171\" alt=\"The Holy Grail of Web Development\" src=\"http://cdn8.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/08/The-Holy-Grail-Of-Web-Development-225x225.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"225\" /></a>I’ve been developing websites for quite a long time, since the 90s to be exact, and over that time the way I work on a project has changed pretty dramatically.</p>\n<p>Like so many other developers I started out working on plain HTML sites on my local computer and then using FTP to send them to a remote server where the world could get to them. That worked great until dynamic sites came around and I could no longer test my code locally resulting in a, well, less than perfect workflow. You see, once I start getting into dynamic sites (I started with Cold Fusion and ASP classic) I developed a habit of developing directly on a remote server, usually the production site, with tools like <a title=\"Adobe Dreamweaver\" href=\"http://www.adobe.com/products/dreamweaver.html\">Dreamweaver</a> that allowed me to connect and work directly on the remote machine. It was in fact this workflow that kept me a loyal Dreamweaver user for the better part of a decade as nothing else at the time could compete with this type of workflow very well.<span id=\"more-5170\"></span></p>\n<p>The next step in my development evolution was a local server. When I was still on Windows I would use <a title=\"XAMPPS\" href=\"http://www.apachefriends.org/en/xampp.html\">XAMPP</a> or even IIS and later when I moved to Mac I discovered <a title=\"MAMP Pro\" href=\"http://www.mamp.info/en/mamp-pro/\">MAMP Pro</a> and finally <a title=\"Softaculous AMPPS\" href=\"http://www.ampps.com/\">AMPPS</a>. For the first time I had a true Apache, MySQL, PHP stack on my local computer that, at least for major versions, could mimic the bulk of my server environments with only minimal modifications. It worked well but it wasn’t perfect. Switching computers could be a nightmare and should anything in the stack become corrupt I was in for some serious trouble. But at least I wasn&#8217;t working on the remote server anymore. This workflow was good, but just not good enough.</p>\n<p>So for the last 5 years I’ve played around with various combinations of MAMP Pro, AMPPS, <a title=\"Homebrew\" href=\"http://brew.sh/\">Homebrew</a>, XAMPP and a few other solutions in search of the perfect server that would mimic my production development almost perfectly, be easily portable and would require a bare minimum amount of maintenance.</p>\n<p>Throughout this time, and in parallel to my quest for the perfect development environment, I have been a heavy user of another now popular technology, <a title=\"Virtual Machines on Wikipedia\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_machine\">virtual machines</a>, which I use to test sites on Windows, Ubuntu and other platforms where I could replicate neither the browser nor the operating system very well using my Mac. While this technology was rather cumbersome 5 years ago when I started using it, today it has matured to the point where you can use a virtual machine as easily as you can use a word processor and with about the same performance level you would expect from the host OS.</p>\n<p>While I’ve been developing locally and using virtual machines for quite some team I had never been able to successfully combine the two goals. Sure I had heard of Puppet, Chef and Vagrant but they seemed to me to be anything but mature and far more of a hassle than getting a proper MAMP or AMPPS environment.</p>\n<p>Finally, last weekend <a title=\"Mark Jaquith on WordPress\" href=\"http://markjaquith.wordpress.com/\">Mark Jaquith</a> changed my opinion on all of this with his <a title=\"WordCamp San Francisco\" href=\"http://sf.wordcamp.org\">WordCamp San Francisco</a> talk titled <a title=\"Watch Mark\'s WordCamp talk\" href=\"http://wordpress.tv/2013/07/28/mark-jaquith-confident-commits-delightful-deploys-2/\">Confident Commits, Delightful Deploys</a>. He pointed out just how mature Vagrant and Puppet had become and how easily they could be utilized to build a local development environment utilizing the same OS and packages I use in production (<a title=\"Ubuntu\" href=\"http://www.ubuntu.com/\">Ubuntu</a>, Apache, NGINX, etc) and requiring only minutes to setup or tear down once the initial configuration was complete.</p>\n<p>The Holy Grail of development environments has been found and it doesn’t require a whole heck of a lot get started.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Install <a title=\"Virtualbox\" href=\"http://www.virtualbox.org\">Virtualbox and its Guest Additions</a>. This is the virtualization engine that will allow your new development environment to run.</li>\n<li>Install <a title=\"Vagrant\" href=\"http://www.vagrantup.com/\">Vagrant</a>. It doesn’t matter what your OS is, this is a free and easy download package that serves as a wrapper around the Virtual machine in Virtualbox. Once configured it will download the image you need, set up the virtual machine and pass it off to a provisioning script to make sure everything you need is installed and configured.</li>\n<li>Get a base configuration. This is easy with sites like <a title=\"https://puphpet.com/\" href=\"https://puphpet.com/\">https://puphpet.com/</a> which allow you to configure what you need for a basic development environment. I started with it and then customized it to meet my needs. Mostly I just changed a few variables to make sure it worked for me a little easier out of the box. You can find <a title=\"My current Vagrant/Puppet script\" href=\"https://github.com/Bit51/Bit51-Vagrant\">my modified configuration on GitHub</a> if you’re interested.</li>\n<li>Start working. Once you have a script getting a development environment is as easy as going to the location of the script you downloaded and typing <em>vagrant up</em> in the terminal.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Why Use Virtual Machines?</h3>\n<p>Yeah, it’s a bit of work to set this all up but once you do there are some serious benefits to this workflow.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>If you’re in a team <strong>everyone will be developing on the same environment</strong>. We’re not there at my day job yet but we’re getting there. Once implemented it won’t matter if folks are on Windows, Mac or Linux. The development environment will be the same throughout allowing us to spend far less time as a team debugging.</li>\n<li><strong>Your development environment can match your production environment</strong>. If you’re deploying to a given environment why not work in that same environment? Again this saves time and sanity in debugging as you’re no longer changing configurations as you push your project up the line.</li>\n<li><strong>Speed and efficiency</strong>. Once you have Vagrant, an install script, and Virtualbox you can switch machines, run up or down new environments and generally get to coding a lot faster without having to spend hours tweaking your local setup to match your servers as closely as possible. For me this is the real benefit at the moment. I can work on any machine I happen to have handy and I no longer have to worry about either setup or whether I’ve configured the new machine to match the old. It just works.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Room to Improve</h3>\n<p>Of course, as I’ve only been using this for a couple of days there is still room for improvement in my setup. In particular I need to work on both my Puppet script and Vagrant box to take into account running PHP over fastcgi as well as a couple of other changes. It’s darn close and I’m sure with a little more time I’ll have it pretty much perfect. Fortunately bringing new environments up and down is so easy that I really have nothing to lose with tweaking it out.</p>\n<h3>Give it a try</h3>\n<p>One of the best things about trying a new method like this is you don’t have to give up the way you currently work. I admit I did delete AMPSS from my computer about a day after starting with Vagrant and <a title=\"Puppet Labs\" href=\"http://puppetlabs.com/\">Puppet</a> as I simply don’t need it anymore but there is no reason you have to. There is nothing to conflict with so your old setup so the only thing you have to lose is a few minutes of your time and an obsolete way of dealing with local development.</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/virtual-machines-the-holy-grail-of-local-web-development/\">Virtual Machines&#8230; The Holy Grail of Local Web Development</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:79:\"http://bit51.com/virtual-machines-the-holy-grail-of-local-web-development/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"WordCamp San Francisco… That’s a Wrap\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:53:\"http://bit51.com/wordcamp-san-francisco-thats-a-wrap/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"http://bit51.com/wordcamp-san-francisco-thats-a-wrap/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 01 Aug 2013 02:06:04 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"Professionalism\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"http://bit51.com/?p=5161\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:551:\"<p>Last weekend I had the opportunity to travel to San Francisco for my third WordCamp of 2013, WordCamp San Francisco. For those of you who are unfamiliar WordCamps are regional WordPress conferences held in cities throughout the world. As part of the WordPress Foundation they&#8217;re cheap (usually only $20), are packed with great speakers and [&#8230;]</p><p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/wordcamp-san-francisco-thats-a-wrap/\">WordCamp San Francisco&#8230; That&#8217;s a Wrap</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Chris Wiegman\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5155:\"<p><a href=\"http://cdn8.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/07/WordCamp-San-Francisco-2013.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-5163\" alt=\"WordCamp San Francisco 2013\" src=\"http://cdn6.bit51.com/content/uploads/2013/07/WordCamp-San-Francisco-2013-225x165.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"165\" /></a>Last weekend I had the opportunity to travel to San Francisco for my third WordCamp of 2013, <a title=\"WordCamp San Francisco 2013\" href=\"http://2013.sf.wordcamp.org/schedule/\" target=\"_blank\">WordCamp San Francisco</a>. For those of you who are unfamiliar <a title=\"WordCamp Central\" href=\"http://central.wordcamp.org/\" target=\"_blank\">WordCamps</a> are regional WordPress conferences held in cities throughout the world. As part of the <a title=\"WordPress Foundation\" href=\"http://wordpressfoundation.org/\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress Foundation</a> they&#8217;re cheap (usually only $20), are packed with great speakers and can be one of the best places to network and discuss all things WordPress.</p>\n<p>Of all the WordCamps held throughout the year WordCamp San Francisco is the king. This is the largest and seemingly most well-funded WordCamp there is. As it is located at the home of <a title=\"Automattic\" href=\"http://automattic.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Automattic</a> (the company behind WordPress.com) it attracts folks from all over the world as attendees, sponsors and speakers providing a depth of knowledge and experience that simply isn&#8217;t available anywhere else.<span id=\"more-5161\"></span></p>\n<p>For any of you who attend conferences regularly you know these events can be hit or miss. Sessions can be shallow, speakers can be horrible and the crowd can be about as exciting as that in the local morgue. Fortunately WordCamp San Francisco is not like that.</p>\n<p>For two days (four if you count travel days) I learned from the best and brightest in the WordPress world. Speakers included <a title=\"Mark Jaquith\" href=\"http://markjaquith.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Mark Jaquith</a> who&#8217;s talk, <a title=\"Confident Commits, Delightful Deploys on WordPress.tv\" href=\"http://wordpress.tv/2013/07/28/mark-jaquith-confident-commits-delightful-deploys-2/\" target=\"_blank\">Confident Commits, Delightful Deploys</a>, has already left me reworking my own development environment by dropping <a title=\"AMPPS\" href=\"http://www.ampps.com/\" target=\"_blank\">AMPPS</a> in favor of a virtual machine. Later <a title=\"Mike Adams on WordPress.org\" href=\"http://profiles.wordpress.org/mdawaffe/\" target=\"_blank\">Mike Adams</a> taught me a thing or two about front-end security (something I rarely find in a conference anymore) and <a title=\"Carrie Dils\" href=\"http://www.carriedils.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Carrie Dils</a> reminded me that collaboration is often preferable to competition in a community like WordPress.</p>\n<p>Unlike other conferences where the learning stops with the sessions, at WordCamp San Francisco the sessions were just the beginning. When the sessions were over I spent the weekend hanging out with <a title=\"BobWP\" href=\"http://bobwp.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Bob Dunn</a> who, along with splitting a cab, introduced me to some incredible folks from all over the WordPress community. I tend to lose track of what is going on outside of code and Bob, a trainer himself, introduced me to a number of folks in the training and content arena that are doing some incredibly awesome things.</p>\n<p>Of course WordPress wasn&#8217;t the only exciting item on my agenda for the weekend. I wound up meeting a long lost cousin of my father&#8217;s who filled me in on a whole side of the family neither myself nor even my father really knows anything about. Among other things it turns out my great-grandparents were members of a <a title=\"Burning Bush Colony\" href=\"http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/ueb07\" target=\"_blank\">religious cult right here in Texas</a> about 100 years ago and my great-grandmother is even burried only a couple of hours from me in Tyler, TX. Considering I never knew I had any relatives outside of Illinois, Iowa and Wisconsin that was quite a surprise in itself.</p>\n<p>Finally, as with all good communities I got the chance to sit back and relax with a number of new friends and old who make their living around WordPress. While learning the next greatest technique might be pretty awesome (and WordCamp San Francisco was chocked full of such awesomeness) it is the community and friends you make that will be there when you get stuck. These are the folks we can turn to for help or just a good laugh when the time is right and there is no replacement for that most important of WordPress attributes, the people.</p>\n<p><em>*<strong>Updated: </strong>Thank you <a title=\"Konstantin Kovshenin\" href=\"http://kovshenin.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Konstantin</a> for pointing out that Automattic is behind <a title=\"WordPress.com\" href=\"http://wordpress.com\" target=\"_blank\">WordPress.com</a>, not WordPress.</em></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://bit51.com/wordcamp-san-francisco-thats-a-wrap/\">WordCamp San Francisco&#8230; That&#8217;s a Wrap</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://bit51.com\">Bit51</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:58:\"http://bit51.com/wordcamp-san-francisco-thats-a-wrap/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"6\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:24:\"Better WP Security 3.5.5\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-5/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"http://bit51.com/better-wp-security-3-5-5/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3